Note: ============================================================================
Note: Compound Type Factories
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Helper that builds an any-shaped RType tagged with a specific S3/S4 class name. Modelling-function returns (lm/glm/htest/anova/histogram) are R objects whose downstream method dispatch keys off the class attribute, so the inferred return type must carry class_name even when the structural base_type is opaque.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns an RType with base_type "any" and the supplied class_name; remaining shape fields empty.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_classed_type" that takes class_name as String returns RType:
    Return a value of type RType with
        base_type as "any",
        dimensions as 0,
        element_type as 0,
        attributes as a dictionary containing nothing,
        is_factor as false,
        factor_levels as 0,
        class_name as class_name
End Process

@Reasoning:
Factory for the generic list RType. R lists are heterogeneous containers - each element can be any type - so element_type is left as any while base_type marks it a list for shape-aware operations.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns an RType with base_type "list" and element_type=any; other fields empty.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_list_type" that takes nothing returns RType:
    Return a value of type RType with
        base_type as "list",
        dimensions as 0,
        element_type as create_any_type,
        attributes as a dictionary containing nothing,
        is_factor as false,
        factor_levels as 0,
        class_name as 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Factory for the matrix RType. A matrix is a numeric vector with a 2-D dim attribute; the dimensions list is initialised empty (filled with [rows,cols] by callers that know the shape) and element_type defaults to numeric, R's matrix default.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns an RType with base_type "matrix", empty dimensions list, element_type=numeric, class_name "matrix".
@End Implementation

Process called "create_matrix_type" that takes nothing returns RType:
    Return a value of type RType with
        base_type as "matrix",
        dimensions as a list containing nothing,
        element_type as create_numeric_type,
        attributes as a dictionary containing nothing,
        is_factor as false,
        factor_levels as 0,
        class_name as "matrix"
End Process

@Reasoning:
Factory for the array RType. An array generalises a matrix to N dimensions via the dim attribute; the dimensions list is empty until a caller supplies the extent vector, and element_type defaults to numeric.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns an RType with base_type "array", empty dimensions list, element_type=numeric, class_name "array".
@End Implementation

Process called "create_array_type" that takes nothing returns RType:
    Return a value of type RType with
        base_type as "array",
        dimensions as a list containing nothing,
        element_type as create_numeric_type,
        attributes as a dictionary containing nothing,
        is_factor as false,
        factor_levels as 0,
        class_name as "array"
End Process

@Reasoning:
Factory for the factor RType. An R factor is an integer vector with a levels attribute mapping codes to labels; is_factor is set true and factor_levels is initialised empty (populated by callers that observe the level set), with element_type integer to reflect the underlying storage.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns an RType with base_type "factor", element_type=integer, is_factor=true, empty factor_levels list, class_name "factor".
@End Implementation

Process called "create_factor_type" that takes nothing returns RType:
    Return a value of type RType with
        base_type as "factor",
        dimensions as 0,
        element_type as create_integer_type,
        attributes as a dictionary containing nothing,
        is_factor as true,
        factor_levels as a list containing nothing,
        class_name as "factor"
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: S3 / S4 Class Registration
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Seeds the S3 class registry with R's most common built-in informal classes (data.frame, factor, lm, glm). Without these, check_s3_method_dispatch and validate_s3_methods would treat every class()-tagged object as user-defined and miss dispatch for the printing/summary methods every R session relies on.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
For each built-in S3 class, builds an RS3ClassInfo with its inheritance chain (e.g. glm inherits from lm) and an empty methods dictionary, then installs it into ctx.s3_classes keyed by class name.
@End Implementation

Process called "register_s3_classes" that takes ctx as RSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Let df_info be a value of type RS3ClassInfo with
        class_name as "data.frame",
        parent_classes as a list containing "list",
        methods as a dictionary containing nothing,
        constructor as 0
    Set ctx.s3_classes at key "data.frame" to df_info

    Let factor_info be a value of type RS3ClassInfo with
        class_name as "factor",
        parent_classes as a list containing "integer",
        methods as a dictionary containing nothing,
        constructor as 0
    Set ctx.s3_classes at key "factor" to factor_info

    Let lm_info be a value of type RS3ClassInfo with
        class_name as "lm",
        parent_classes as a list containing nothing,
        methods as a dictionary containing nothing,
        constructor as 0
    Set ctx.s3_classes at key "lm" to lm_info

    Let glm_info be a value of type RS3ClassInfo with
        class_name as "glm",
        parent_classes as a list containing "lm",
        methods as a dictionary containing nothing,
        constructor as 0
    Set ctx.s3_classes at key "glm" to glm_info
End Process

@Reasoning:
Seeds the S4 registry. The methods package defines a small set of formal base classes (numeric, character, logical) used as slot types in user setClass() calls; registering them lets validate_s4_methods confirm that a slot's declared class is known.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
For each base S4 class, builds an RS4ClassInfo with empty slots/methods and a null validity_function, then installs it into ctx.s4_classes keyed by class name.
@End Implementation

Process called "register_s4_classes" that takes ctx as RSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Let numeric_info be a value of type RS4ClassInfo with
        class_name as "numeric",
        slots as a dictionary containing nothing,
        parent_classes as a list containing nothing,
        methods as a dictionary containing nothing,
        validity_function as 0
    Set ctx.s4_classes at key "numeric" to numeric_info

    Let character_info be a value of type RS4ClassInfo with
        class_name as "character",
        slots as a dictionary containing nothing,
        parent_classes as a list containing nothing,
        methods as a dictionary containing nothing,
        validity_function as 0
    Set ctx.s4_classes at key "character" to character_info

    Let logical_info be a value of type RS4ClassInfo with
        class_name as "logical",
        slots as a dictionary containing nothing,
        parent_classes as a list containing nothing,
        methods as a dictionary containing nothing,
        validity_function as 0
    Set ctx.s4_classes at key "logical" to logical_info
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: S3 Method Detection and Dispatch
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Detects whether a function name follows R's S3 method naming convention generic.class (e.g. print.data.frame, summary.lm). A name qualifies as an S3 method when it contains a dot separating a registered generic from a known class, distinguishing genuine methods from ordinary dotted names like read.csv.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Scans func_name for a '.' separator. If a dot exists and the substring after the first dot names a class present in ctx-independent built-in class set (data.frame/factor/lm/glm/matrix/list/numeric/character/logical), returns true. Implemented without ctx because the function-declaration site only has the name. Returns false when no dot or unrecognised class suffix.
@End Implementation

Process called "check_is_s3_method" that takes func_name as String returns Boolean:
    Let dot_index be string_index_of_char with func_name and 46
    If dot_index is less than 0:
        Return false
    End If

    Let name_len be string_length_of with func_name
    Let suffix_start be dot_index plus 1
    If suffix_start is greater than or equal to name_len:
        Return false
    End If

    Let known_classes be a list containing "data.frame", "factor", "lm", "glm", "matrix", "list", "numeric", "character", "logical", "default"
    For Each cls in known_classes:
        Let matched be string_ends_with_at with func_name and suffix_start and cls
        If matched:
            Return true
        End If
    End For
    Return false
End Process

@Reasoning:
Detects S4 method definitions. In source, S4 methods are declared via setMethod(), but at the function-name level the analyzer recognises names carrying the S4 marker prefix that R's method tables use (".__T__"). Keeping S3 and S4 detection separate avoids misclassifying ordinary dotted base names.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns true only when func_name begins with R's S4 method-table marker ".__T__"; otherwise false. The setMethod() call site itself is handled during call analysis.
@End Implementation

Process called "check_is_s4_method" that takes func_name as String returns Boolean:
    Let marker be ".__T__"
    Return string_starts_with with func_name and marker
End Process

@Reasoning:
Resolves an unqualified generic call to a concrete S3 method by walking the class chain of the first argument. R's UseMethod dispatch tries generic.class for each class in the object's class vector (most specific first), falling back to generic.default. The analyzer reproduces this by looking up generic.<class> in the function environment for each candidate class.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Infers the type of the first argument (if any) to obtain its class_name; walks that class plus its registered parent_classes from ctx.s3_classes, building candidate method names "<generic>.<class>" and looking each up via lookup_r_function. Returns the first match, else tries "<generic>.default", else returns 0.
@End Implementation

Process called "check_s3_method_dispatch" that takes func_name as String, arguments as List, ctx as RSemanticContext returns RFunction:
    Let class_name be 0
    If arguments is not equal to 0:
        Let arg_count be list_length with arguments
        If arg_count is greater than 0:
            Let first_arg be list_get with arguments and 0
            Let arg_type be infer_r_expression_type with first_arg and ctx
            Set class_name to arg_type.class_name
        End If
    End If

    If class_name is not equal to 0:
        Let primary_candidate be string_join_three with func_name and "." and class_name
        Let primary_method be lookup_r_function with primary_candidate and ctx
        If primary_method is not equal to 0:
            Return primary_method
        End If

        If ctx.s3_classes contains key class_name:
            Let class_info as RS3ClassInfo be ctx.s3_classes at key class_name
            Let parents be class_info.parent_classes
            If parents is not equal to 0:
                Let parent_count be list_length with parents
                Let pi be 0
                While pi is less than parent_count:
                    Let parent_cls be list_get with parents and pi
                    Let parent_candidate be string_join_three with func_name and "." and parent_cls
                    Let parent_method be lookup_r_function with parent_candidate and ctx
                    If parent_method is not equal to 0:
                        Return parent_method
                    End If
                    Set pi to pi plus 1
                End While
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Let default_candidate be string_join_three with func_name and "." and "default"
    Let default_method be lookup_r_function with default_candidate and ctx
    If default_method is not equal to 0:
        Return default_method
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: String Utility Helpers (analyzer-local, over string primitives)
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Analyzer-local thin wrapper over the imported string-equality primitive so the dispatch and detection routines read clearly. Centralising it keeps the comparison semantics (byte-exact) consistent everywhere the analyzer compares R identifiers.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Delegates to the StringCore string_equals primitive and returns its boolean result.
@End Implementation

Process called "string_values_equal" that takes a as String, b as String returns Boolean:
    Let result be string_equals with a and b
    If result is not equal to 0:
        Return true
    End If
    Return false
End Process

@Reasoning:
Returns the byte length of an R identifier, used by the S3/S4 name-convention checks to bound substring extraction. Delegates to the string-length primitive.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Calls the StringCore string_length primitive and returns its integer result.
@End Implementation

Process called "string_length_of" that takes s as String returns Integer:
    Return string_length with s
End Process

@Reasoning:
Finds the first index of a given byte (passed as its integer code) within a string, or -1 if absent. Used to locate the '.' separator in S3 method names. Implemented directly over byte access so it does not depend on a higher-level search primitive that may not be exported here.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Iterates indices 0..length-1, comparing each byte (via string_char_at) to the target code; returns the first matching index, or -1 when exhausted.
@End Implementation

Process called "string_index_of_char" that takes s as String, target_code as Integer returns Integer:
    Let len be string_length with s
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than len:
        Let ch be string_char_at with s and i
        If ch is equal to target_code:
            Return i
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return 0 minus 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Tests whether the substring of s beginning at start_index equals the candidate pattern exactly (i.e. pattern is the tail of s from start_index). Used by S3 method detection to check the class suffix after the '.' without materialising a substring. Implemented by byte-comparing pattern against s starting at start_index and requiring the lengths to line up so a longer s does not spuriously match a shorter pattern.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Computes both lengths; returns false unless start_index plus pattern length equals the length of s (the pattern must reach exactly the end of s). Then byte-compares pattern[i] against s[start_index+i] for all i, returning false on the first mismatch and true when all bytes agree.
@End Implementation

Process called "string_ends_with_at" that takes s as String, start_index as Integer, pattern as String returns Boolean:
    Let s_len be string_length with s
    Let p_len be string_length with pattern
    Let end_index be start_index plus p_len
    If end_index is not equal to s_len:
        Return false
    End If
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than p_len:
        Let pc be string_char_at with pattern and i
        Let sc be string_char_at with s and start_index plus i
        If pc is not equal to sc:
            Return false
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return true
End Process

@Reasoning:
Tests whether s begins with the prefix pattern. Used by S4 method detection to recognise R's ".__T__" method-table marker. Implemented by byte-comparison so it depends only on the char-access primitive.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns false when s is shorter than pattern. Otherwise byte-compares pattern[i] against s[i] for all i in 0..prefix length, returning false on the first mismatch and true when every byte matches.
@End Implementation

Process called "string_starts_with" that takes s as String, pattern as String returns Boolean:
    Let s_len be string_length with s
    Let p_len be string_length with pattern
    If s_len is less than p_len:
        Return false
    End If
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than p_len:
        Let pc be string_char_at with pattern and i
        Let sc be string_char_at with s and i
        If pc is not equal to sc:
            Return false
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return true
End Process

@Reasoning:
Concatenates three strings in order (used to assemble "<generic>.<class>" dispatch candidate names) by chaining the string-concat primitive, avoiding nested call-arg expressions that the compiler cannot lower in a single pass.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Concatenates a and b into a temporary, then concatenates that with c, returning the final string.
@End Implementation

Process called "string_join_three" that takes a as String, b as String, c as String returns String:
    Let ab be string_concat with a and b
    Let abc be string_concat with ab and c
    Return abc
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Assignment Analyzers (per operator)
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Shared core for the local-scope assignment operators <- and =. It records the assignment target as a binding in the CURRENT environment: if the target name already exists there its inferred type is refreshed and its last-assignment line bumped; otherwise a new RVariable is created. Only identifier targets introduce bindings - complex targets like df$col or x[i] are replacement-function calls and are analyzed as accesses rather than declarations.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads target.name. If target is an identifier and the current environment already has the binding, updates its type to value_type. Otherwise constructs a fresh RVariable (type=value_type, scope=current env name) and installs it into ctx.current_environment.variables. Non-identifier targets are routed to analyze_r_node for sub-expression analysis.
@End Implementation

Process called "analyze_local_binding" that takes target as RASTNode, value_type as RType, ctx as RSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Let target_kind be target.node_type
    Let is_identifier be string_values_equal with target_kind and "Identifier"
    If is_identifier:
        Let target_name be target.name
        If ctx.current_environment.variables contains key target_name:
            Let existing as RVariable be ctx.current_environment.variables at key target_name
            Set existing.type to value_type
            Set existing.last_access_line to target.line
            Set ctx.current_environment.variables at key target_name to existing
        Otherwise:
            Let new_var be a value of type RVariable with
                name as target_name,
                type as value_type,
                is_constant as false,
                scope as ctx.current_environment.name,
                first_assignment_line as target.line,
                last_access_line as 0
            Set ctx.current_environment.variables at key target_name to new_var
        End If
    Otherwise:
        Call analyze_r_node with target and ctx
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
The <- operator is R's canonical local assignment; semantics are identical to analyze_local_binding so this routine delegates, keeping the operator-specific entry point the analyze_r_assignment switch expects.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Delegates to analyze_local_binding with the same target, value_type, and ctx.
@End Implementation

Process called "analyze_left_assignment" that takes target as RASTNode, value_type as RType, ctx as RSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Call analyze_local_binding with target and value_type and ctx
End Process

@Reasoning:
The = operator at top level or in a block behaves as a local assignment (distinct from its use as a named-argument separator inside calls, which the parser models separately). Semantics match <-, so it delegates to the shared local-binding core.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Delegates to analyze_local_binding.
@End Implementation

Process called "analyze_equal_assignment" that takes target as RASTNode, value_type as RType, ctx as RSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Call analyze_local_binding with target and value_type and ctx
End Process

@Reasoning:
The -> operator is right-assignment: value -> target. The target is on the right syntactically but the binding semantics are identical to <-, so after the parser has normalised operand order this delegates to the shared local-binding core.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Delegates to analyze_local_binding with the target (already extracted as the binding name by the caller).
@End Implementation

Process called "analyze_right_assignment" that takes target as RASTNode, value_type as RType, ctx as RSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Call analyze_local_binding with target and value_type and ctx
End Process

@Reasoning:
Shared core for the super-assignment operators <<- and ->>. These do NOT bind in the current environment; instead they walk the parent chain looking for an existing binding to mutate, and only if none is found do they create the binding in the global environment. This routine reproduces that climb so the analyzer's symbol tables reflect R's true scoping for closures that modify enclosing state.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
For identifier targets: walks env=current.parent_env upward; at the first environment whose variables contain the target name, refreshes that binding's type and returns. If the chain is exhausted, locates the global environment (the root with is_global=true / parent_env=null) and installs a new RVariable there. Non-identifier targets fall back to analyze_r_node.
@End Implementation

Process called "analyze_super_binding" that takes target as RASTNode, value_type as RType, ctx as RSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Let target_kind be target.node_type
    Let is_identifier be string_values_equal with target_kind and "Identifier"
    If is_identifier is equal to false:
        Call analyze_r_node with target and ctx
        Return
    End If

    Let target_name be target.name

    Note: Climb the enclosing environments (skip the current one)
    Let search_env be ctx.current_environment.parent_env
    While search_env is not equal to 0:
        If search_env.variables contains key target_name:
            Let existing as RVariable be search_env.variables at key target_name
            Set existing.type to value_type
            Set existing.last_access_line to target.line
            Set search_env.variables at key target_name to existing
            Return
        End If
        Set search_env to search_env.parent_env
    End While

    Note: Not found in any enclosing scope - bind in the global environment
    Let global_env be ctx.current_environment
    While global_env.parent_env is not equal to 0:
        Set global_env to global_env.parent_env
    End While
    Let new_var be a value of type RVariable with
        name as target_name,
        type as value_type,
        is_constant as false,
        scope as global_env.name,
        first_assignment_line as target.line,
        last_access_line as 0
    Set global_env.variables at key target_name to new_var
End Process

@Reasoning:
<<- is left super-assignment; it mutates an enclosing/global binding rather than a local one. Semantics match the shared super-binding core.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Delegates to analyze_super_binding.
@End Implementation

Process called "analyze_global_left_assignment" that takes target as RASTNode, value_type as RType, ctx as RSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Call analyze_super_binding with target and value_type and ctx
End Process

@Reasoning:
->> is right super-assignment (value ->> target); identical scoping semantics to <<- after operand normalisation, so it delegates to the shared super-binding core.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Delegates to analyze_super_binding.
@End Implementation

Process called "analyze_global_right_assignment" that takes target as RASTNode, value_type as RType, ctx as RSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Call analyze_super_binding with target and value_type and ctx
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Parameter, Control-flow, and Vector Analyzers
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Analyzes a single formal parameter node from a function declaration. R parameters may be bare (x), defaulted (x = 1), or the variadic dots (...). The parser models a defaulted parameter as an assignment node (name on the left, default expr on the right) and a bare parameter as an identifier. This routine inspects which shape it received and produces the corresponding RParameter, inferring the parameter's type from its default when present.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
If the node is an assignment, treats node.target/left as the parameter name and node.value as the default expression - sets has_default=true, default_value=the rendered name, and infers type from the default via infer_r_expression_type. If the node's name is "...", sets is_variadic=true. Otherwise builds a bare any-typed parameter. Returns the constructed RParameter.
@End Implementation

Process called "analyze_r_parameter" that takes param as RASTNode, ctx as RSemanticContext returns RParameter:
    Let kind be param.node_type
    Let is_default be string_values_equal with kind and "Assignment"
    If is_default:
        Let pname_node as RASTNode be param.target
        Let pname be pname_node.name
        Let default_expr be param.value
        Let inferred be create_any_type
        If default_expr is not equal to 0:
            Set inferred to infer_r_expression_type with default_expr and ctx
        End If
        Return a value of type RParameter with
            name as pname,
            type as inferred,
            has_default as true,
            default_value as pname,
            is_variadic as false
    End If

    Let pname be param.name
    Let is_dots be string_values_equal with pname and "..."
    If is_dots:
        Return a value of type RParameter with
            name as "...",
            type as create_any_type,
            has_default as false,
            default_value as 0,
            is_variadic as true
    End If

    Return a value of type RParameter with
        name as pname,
        type as create_any_type,
        has_default as false,
        default_value as 0,
        is_variadic as false
End Process

@Reasoning:
Analyzes an R if/else statement. R's if is an expression: the condition is evaluated for its (logical) value and each branch is analyzed in the current environment (R does not introduce a new scope for if blocks). Surfacing analysis of both branches lets undefined-symbol and type warnings inside either arm be reported.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads the condition, then-branch, and else-branch from the node's standard fields. Analyzes the condition via analyze_r_node and infers its type, warning if the inferred base_type is neither logical nor any (R coerces but a non-logical scalar condition is a common bug). Analyzes the then-branch and, when present (non-zero), the else-branch.
@End Implementation

Process called "analyze_r_if_statement" that takes node as RASTNode, ctx as RSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Let condition be node.value
    Let then_branch be node.body
    Let else_branch be node.target

    If condition is not equal to 0:
        Call analyze_r_node with condition and ctx
        Let cond_type be infer_r_expression_type with condition and ctx
        Let is_logical be string_values_equal with cond_type.base_type and "logical"
        Let is_any be string_values_equal with cond_type.base_type and "any"
        If is_logical is equal to false:
            If is_any is equal to false:
                Let warn be string_concat with "If condition is not logical, base type: " and cond_type.base_type
                Add warn to end of ctx.warning_list
            End If
        End If
    End If

    If then_branch is not equal to 0:
        Call analyze_r_node with then_branch and ctx
    End If
    If else_branch is not equal to 0:
        Call analyze_r_node with else_branch and ctx
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Analyzes an R for loop (for (var in seq) body). The loop variable is introduced as a binding in the current environment for the duration of the loop, typed as the element type of the sequence so uses of the loop variable in the body infer correctly. The sequence expression and body are then analyzed.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads the loop-variable identifier, the sequence expression, and the body. Analyzes the sequence, infers its type, and derives the loop-variable type from the sequence's element_type when available (falling back to any). Installs the loop variable as an RVariable in the current environment, then analyzes the body.
@End Implementation

Process called "analyze_r_for_loop" that takes node as RASTNode, ctx as RSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Let loop_var_node as RASTNode be node.target
    Let sequence be node.value
    Let body be node.body

    Note: Analyze the sequence first and infer the element type
    Let elem_type be create_any_type
    If sequence is not equal to 0:
        Call analyze_r_node with sequence and ctx
        Let seq_type be infer_r_expression_type with sequence and ctx
        If seq_type.element_type is not equal to 0:
            Set elem_type to seq_type.element_type
        End If
    End If

    Note: Bind the loop variable in the current environment
    If loop_var_node is not equal to 0:
        Let var_name be loop_var_node.name
        Let loop_var be a value of type RVariable with
            name as var_name,
            type as elem_type,
            is_constant as false,
            scope as ctx.current_environment.name,
            first_assignment_line as node.line,
            last_access_line as node.line
        Set ctx.current_environment.variables at key var_name to loop_var
    End If

    If body is not equal to 0:
        Call analyze_r_node with body and ctx
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Analyzes an R while loop. The condition is analyzed and checked for a logical (or any) type; the body is analyzed in the current environment. Like if, while does not introduce a new scope in R.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads the condition and body. Analyzes the condition, infers its type, and warns when it is neither logical nor any. Analyzes the body.
@End Implementation

Process called "analyze_r_while_loop" that takes node as RASTNode, ctx as RSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Let condition be node.value
    Let body be node.body

    If condition is not equal to 0:
        Call analyze_r_node with condition and ctx
        Let cond_type be infer_r_expression_type with condition and ctx
        Let is_logical be string_values_equal with cond_type.base_type and "logical"
        Let is_any be string_values_equal with cond_type.base_type and "any"
        If is_logical is equal to false:
            If is_any is equal to false:
                Let warn be string_concat with "While condition is not logical, base type: " and cond_type.base_type
                Add warn to end of ctx.warning_list
            End If
        End If
    End If

    If body is not equal to 0:
        Call analyze_r_node with body and ctx
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Analyzes a vectorized operation (c(...) construction or element-wise arithmetic over vectors). Every element/operand expression is analyzed so identifier uses are recorded, and the element types are collected to detect heterogeneous combination (R coerces to the highest common type: logical < integer < numeric < complex < character).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Iterates node.arguments (the c() elements or operands), analyzing each via analyze_r_node and inferring its type. Tracks whether more than one distinct base_type was seen; when so, appends an informational note that coercion will occur. No error is raised because heterogeneous c() is legal R.
@End Implementation

Process called "analyze_r_vector_operation" that takes node as RASTNode, ctx as RSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Let elements be node.arguments
    If elements is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    Let count be list_length with elements
    Let first_base be 0
    Let mixed be false
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let elem be list_get with elements and i
        Call analyze_r_node with elem and ctx
        Let elem_type be infer_r_expression_type with elem and ctx
        Let elem_base be elem_type.base_type
        If first_base is equal to 0:
            Set first_base to elem_base
        Otherwise:
            Let same be string_values_equal with first_base and elem_base
            If same is equal to false:
                Set mixed to true
            End If
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    If mixed:
        Add "Vector contains mixed element types - R will coerce to a common type" to end of ctx.warning_list
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Catch-all for AST node kinds that have no dedicated analyzer (literals, plain expressions, blocks, member access, etc.). To remain a sound semantic walk it must still recurse into any sub-expressions so symbol uses inside them are recorded - silently dropping unknown nodes would hide undefined-variable warnings in nested expressions.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
If the node carries an arguments list, analyzes each argument. Recurses into the standard child slots (target, value, body, initializer, dataframe, accessor, response) when each is non-zero, dispatching back through analyze_r_node. Identifier nodes additionally bump their binding's last_access_line via infer_identifier_type so use-tracking stays accurate.
@End Implementation

Process called "analyze_generic_node" that takes node as RASTNode, ctx as RSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Let kind be node.node_type
    Let is_identifier be string_values_equal with kind and "Identifier"
    If is_identifier:
        Let ignored be infer_identifier_type with node and ctx
        Return
    End If

    Let args be node.arguments
    If args is not equal to 0:
        Let arg_count be list_length with args
        Let ai be 0
        While ai is less than arg_count:
            Let arg be list_get with args and ai
            Call analyze_r_node with arg and ctx
            Set ai to ai plus 1
        End While
    End If

    Let child_target be node.target
    If child_target is not equal to 0:
        Call analyze_r_node with child_target and ctx
    End If
    Let child_value be node.value
    If child_value is not equal to 0:
        Call analyze_r_node with child_value and ctx
    End If
    Let child_body be node.body
    If child_body is not equal to 0:
        Call analyze_r_node with child_body and ctx
    End If
    Let child_init be node.initializer
    If child_init is not equal to 0:
        Call analyze_r_node with child_init and ctx
    End If
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Formula, Data-frame Access, and Interaction Analyzers
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Validates a variable referenced inside a formula (y ~ x). Formula variables are resolved against the current environment; if the name is unknown R will look it up in the data argument at fit time, so an unresolved formula variable is a warning (deferred resolution) rather than an error. Resolving it here also records the access for use-tracking.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
If the node is an identifier, looks the name up via lookup_r_variable. On hit, bumps last_access_line. On miss, appends a warning that the variable must be supplied via the model's data argument. Non-identifier formula terms (e.g. transformations log(x)) are routed to analyze_r_node for full sub-expression analysis.
@End Implementation

Process called "validate_formula_variable" that takes node as RASTNode, ctx as RSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Let kind be node.node_type
    Let is_identifier be string_values_equal with kind and "Identifier"
    If is_identifier:
        Let var_name be node.name
        Let variable be lookup_r_variable with var_name and ctx
        If variable is not equal to 0:
            Set variable.last_access_line to node.line
        Otherwise:
            Let warn be string_concat with "Formula variable not in scope, expected in data argument: " and var_name
            Add warn to end of ctx.warning_list
        End If
        Return
    End If
    Call analyze_r_node with node and ctx
End Process

@Reasoning:
Analyzes an interaction term (a:b) in a model formula. Both operands are formula variables whose presence must be validated. The interaction itself does not introduce new bindings; it composes existing predictors, so each operand is routed through validate_formula_variable.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads the interaction's two operands from its left/target and right/value child slots. Validates each present operand via validate_formula_variable.
@End Implementation

Process called "analyze_r_interaction" that takes node as RASTNode, ctx as RSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Let left_term be node.target
    Let right_term be node.value
    If left_term is not equal to 0:
        Call validate_formula_variable with left_term and ctx
    End If
    If right_term is not equal to 0:
        Call validate_formula_variable with right_term and ctx
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Analyzes column access on a data frame (df$col or df[["col"]]). The accessor names a column; the result type is the column's element type. Because the analyzer does not track each frame's exact column schema by default, the column access yields the data frame's recorded element type (any when unknown), while still validating that the accessor is a name or character index.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads the accessor node. If it is an identifier or string, records the column name access (no error). Infers the result type from df_type.element_type when present, else any. Appends a warning only if the accessor is a non-name, non-string expression (illegal for $ access). Recurses into the accessor via analyze_r_node when it is a computed expression.
@End Implementation

Process called "analyze_column_access" that takes accessor as RASTNode, df_type as RType, ctx as RSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    If accessor is equal to 0:
        Add "Data frame column access has no accessor" to end of ctx.error_list
        Return
    End If

    Let kind be accessor.node_type
    Let is_identifier be string_values_equal with kind and "Identifier"
    Let is_string be string_values_equal with kind and "Literal"
    If is_identifier:
        Return
    End If
    If is_string:
        Return
    End If

    Note: Computed accessor - analyze the expression and verify it yields a character/integer index
    Call analyze_r_node with accessor and ctx
    Let acc_type be infer_r_expression_type with accessor and ctx
    Let is_char be string_values_equal with acc_type.base_type and "character"
    Let is_int be string_values_equal with acc_type.base_type and "integer"
    Let is_any be string_values_equal with acc_type.base_type and "any"
    If is_char is equal to false:
        If is_int is equal to false:
            If is_any is equal to false:
                Add "Data frame column accessor is not a name, character, or integer index" to end of ctx.warning_list
            End If
        End If
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Analyzes row access on a data frame (df[i, ]). The row index must be an integer, logical (mask), or character (row name) expression. The result preserves the data.frame class (a row subset is still a data frame). The accessor expression is analyzed and its type validated.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads the accessor; if absent (df[, ] selecting all rows) returns without error. Otherwise analyzes the accessor and infers its type, warning when the base_type is none of integer/logical/character/any (an invalid row index expression).
@End Implementation

Process called "analyze_row_access" that takes accessor as RASTNode, df_type as RType, ctx as RSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    If accessor is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    Call analyze_r_node with accessor and ctx
    Let acc_type be infer_r_expression_type with accessor and ctx
    Let base be acc_type.base_type
    Let is_int be string_values_equal with base and "integer"
    Let is_logical be string_values_equal with base and "logical"
    Let is_char be string_values_equal with base and "character"
    Let is_numeric be string_values_equal with base and "numeric"
    Let is_any be string_values_equal with base and "any"
    If is_int is equal to false:
        If is_logical is equal to false:
            If is_char is equal to false:
                If is_numeric is equal to false:
                    If is_any is equal to false:
                        Add "Data frame row index is not integer, logical, character, or numeric" to end of ctx.warning_list
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Analyzes a two-dimensional subset access (df[rows, cols]). Both the row and column accessors are validated as index expressions and the result preserves the data.frame class. This composes the row and column analyzers over the accessor's two operands.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Treats the accessor node as carrying two index operands in its target/left (row) and value/right (col) slots. Routes the row operand through analyze_row_access and the column operand through analyze_column_access, passing df_type to each. A bare single accessor (no second operand) is treated as a row access.
@End Implementation

Process called "analyze_subset_access" that takes accessor as RASTNode, df_type as RType, ctx as RSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    If accessor is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    Let row_part be accessor.target
    Let col_part be accessor.value
    If row_part is equal to 0:
        If col_part is equal to 0:
            Note: Single-dimension subset - treat the whole accessor as a row index
            Call analyze_row_access with accessor and df_type and ctx
            Return
        End If
    End If

    If row_part is not equal to 0:
        Call analyze_row_access with row_part and df_type and ctx
    End If
    If col_part is not equal to 0:
        Call analyze_column_access with col_part and df_type and ctx
    End If
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Function-call Argument Validation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Validates a call site against the resolved function's formal parameter list. R's matching rules are: positional and named arguments may be mixed; a variadic "..." parameter absorbs any number of trailing/unmatched arguments; parameters with defaults are optional. The check therefore enforces a minimum required-argument count (formals without defaults, excluding dots) and an upper bound only when no dots parameter exists.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Counts the supplied arguments and walks the function's parameters to compute required_count (params with has_default=false and not variadic) and whether a variadic param exists. If supplied < required_count, appends an arity error. If no variadic param exists and supplied > total params, appends a too-many-arguments error. Otherwise the call is well-formed at arity level.
@End Implementation

Process called "validate_r_function_arguments" that takes r_function as RFunction, arguments as List, ctx as RSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Let supplied be 0
    If arguments is not equal to 0:
        Set supplied to list_length with arguments
    End If

    Let params be r_function.parameters
    Let total_params be 0
    Let required_count be 0
    Let has_variadic be false
    If params is not equal to 0:
        Set total_params to list_length with params
        Let pi be 0
        While pi is less than total_params:
            Let p as RParameter be list_get with params and pi
            If p.is_variadic:
                Set has_variadic to true
            Otherwise:
                If p.has_default is equal to false:
                    Set required_count to required_count plus 1
                End If
            End If
            Set pi to pi plus 1
        End While
    End If

    If supplied is less than required_count:
        Let err be string_concat with "Too few arguments in call to '" and r_function.name
        Let err2 be string_concat with err and "'"
        Add err2 to end of ctx.error_list
        Return
    End If

    If has_variadic is equal to false:
        If supplied is greater than total_params:
            Let err be string_concat with "Too many arguments in call to '" and r_function.name
            Let err2 be string_concat with err and "'"
            Add err2 to end of ctx.error_list
        End If
    End If
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Type Inference for Compound Expressions
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Infers the type of a c(...) vector construction. R determines a vector's type by coercing all elements to the highest common atomic type along the hierarchy logical < integer < numeric < complex < character. The inferred RType carries that base_type and records the element_type so downstream indexing knows the element shape.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Iterates the construction's element expressions, inferring each element's base_type and folding it into a running rank along the coercion hierarchy. Maps the final rank back to a base_type, builds the corresponding scalar element RType, and returns a vector RType whose element_type is that scalar (empty/any vector yields an any element).
@End Implementation

Process called "infer_vector_type" that takes expr as RASTNode, ctx as RSemanticContext returns RType:
    Let elements be expr.arguments
    Let best_rank be 0
    If elements is not equal to 0:
        Let count be list_length with elements
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than count:
            Let elem be list_get with elements and i
            Let elem_type be infer_r_expression_type with elem and ctx
            Let rank be r_type_rank with elem_type.base_type
            If rank is greater than best_rank:
                Set best_rank to rank
            End If
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    End If

    Let element_type be r_rank_to_type with best_rank
    Return a value of type RType with
        base_type as element_type.base_type,
        dimensions as 0,
        element_type as element_type,
        attributes as a dictionary containing nothing,
        is_factor as false,
        factor_levels as 0,
        class_name as 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Maps an atomic base_type name to its rank in R's implicit coercion hierarchy. Used by vector and binary-operation inference to pick the result type when operands differ. Higher rank wins: logical(1) < integer(2) < numeric(3) < complex(4) < character(5); unknown/any maps to 0 so it never dominates a concrete type.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Compares the supplied base_type string against each hierarchy level and returns its integer rank; returns 0 for any unrecognised type.
@End Implementation

Process called "r_type_rank" that takes base_type as String returns Integer:
    Let is_logical be string_values_equal with base_type and "logical"
    If is_logical:
        Return 1
    End If
    Let is_integer be string_values_equal with base_type and "integer"
    If is_integer:
        Return 2
    End If
    Let is_numeric be string_values_equal with base_type and "numeric"
    If is_numeric:
        Return 3
    End If
    Let is_complex be string_values_equal with base_type and "complex"
    If is_complex:
        Return 4
    End If
    Let is_character be string_values_equal with base_type and "character"
    If is_character:
        Return 5
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Inverse of r_type_rank: builds the scalar RType for a given coercion rank. Used to materialise the element type of an inferred vector or binary-operation result from the winning rank.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Switches on the integer rank, returning the matching create_*_type factory result; rank 0 (or unrecognised) yields create_any_type.
@End Implementation

Process called "r_rank_to_type" that takes rank as Integer returns RType:
    If rank is equal to 1:
        Return create_logical_type
    End If
    If rank is equal to 2:
        Return create_integer_type
    End If
    If rank is equal to 3:
        Return create_numeric_type
    End If
    If rank is equal to 4:
        Return create_complex_type
    End If
    If rank is equal to 5:
        Return create_character_type
    End If
    Return create_any_type
End Process

@Reasoning:
Infers the type of a data.frame construction (data.frame(col1=..., col2=...)). The result is always the data.frame type; each column-defining argument is analyzed so its constituent expressions are checked, but the aggregate shape is the canonical data frame.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Iterates the construction's column arguments, inferring each so any nested identifier uses are exercised, then returns create_data_frame_type as the aggregate result.
@End Implementation

Process called "infer_data_frame_type" that takes expr as RASTNode, ctx as RSemanticContext returns RType:
    Let columns be expr.arguments
    If columns is not equal to 0:
        Let count be list_length with columns
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than count:
            Let col be list_get with columns and i
            Let ignored be infer_r_expression_type with col and ctx
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    End If
    Return create_data_frame_type
End Process

@Reasoning:
Infers the result type of a binary operation. R arithmetic/comparison operators are vectorized: arithmetic (+ - * / ^) yields the coerced common type of the operands; relational and logical operators (== < > & |) yield logical. The result is computed by ranking both operand types and either taking the higher rank (arithmetic) or returning logical (comparison/logical).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Infers the left and right operand types from the node's left/target and right/value slots. Reads the node's operator marker. If the operator is relational or logical, returns logical. Otherwise (arithmetic) takes the max of the two operand ranks via r_type_rank and materialises the result via r_rank_to_type. Missing operands degrade to any.
@End Implementation

Process called "infer_binary_operation_type" that takes expr as RASTNode, ctx as RSemanticContext returns RType:
    Let op be expr.operator
    Let is_comparison be false
    If op is not equal to 0:
        Let is_eq be string_values_equal with op and "=="
        Let is_ne be string_values_equal with op and "!="
        Let is_lt be string_values_equal with op and "<"
        Let is_gt be string_values_equal with op and ">"
        Let is_le be string_values_equal with op and "<="
        Let is_ge be string_values_equal with op and ">="
        Let is_and be string_values_equal with op and "&"
        Let is_or be string_values_equal with op and "|"
        If is_eq:
            Set is_comparison to true
        End If
        If is_ne:
            Set is_comparison to true
        End If
        If is_lt:
            Set is_comparison to true
        End If
        If is_gt:
            Set is_comparison to true
        End If
        If is_le:
            Set is_comparison to true
        End If
        If is_ge:
            Set is_comparison to true
        End If
        If is_and:
            Set is_comparison to true
        End If
        If is_or:
            Set is_comparison to true
        End If
    End If

    If is_comparison:
        Return create_logical_type
    End If

    Let left_operand be expr.target
    Let right_operand be expr.value
    Let left_rank be 0
    Let right_rank be 0
    If left_operand is not equal to 0:
        Let lt be infer_r_expression_type with left_operand and ctx
        Set left_rank to r_type_rank with lt.base_type
    End If
    If right_operand is not equal to 0:
        Let rt be infer_r_expression_type with right_operand and ctx
        Set right_rank to r_type_rank with rt.base_type
    End If

    Let result_rank be left_rank
    If right_rank is greater than result_rank:
        Set result_rank to right_rank
    End If
    Return r_rank_to_type with result_rank
End Process

@Reasoning:
Infers the result type of a unary operation. R unary operators are: arithmetic negation (-x, +x) which preserves the operand's numeric type, and logical negation (!x) which yields logical. The result therefore depends on the operator: ! produces logical, otherwise the operand type is propagated.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads the operator marker and the operand from the node's right/value slot. If the operator is logical-not, returns logical. Otherwise infers and returns the operand's type (any when the operand is absent).
@End Implementation

Process called "infer_unary_operation_type" that takes expr as RASTNode, ctx as RSemanticContext returns RType:
    Let op be expr.operator
    If op is not equal to 0:
        Let is_not be string_values_equal with op and "!"
        If is_not:
            Return create_logical_type
        End If
    End If

    Let operand be expr.value
    If operand is not equal to 0:
        Return infer_r_expression_type with operand and ctx
    End If
    Return create_any_type
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Package Definition Loading
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Loads the exported function/type definitions for a package named in a library()/require() call. The analyzer ships models for the standard packages (base/stats/utils/graphics already loaded at startup); for those, re-loading is a no-op. For recognised add-on packages it installs their characteristic exports so subsequent calls resolve; for genuinely unknown packages it records that analysis will fall back to any-typed resolution for that package's symbols.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Compares package_name against the set of packages already modelled at startup (base/stats/utils/graphics/methods/grDevices/datasets); if present, returns (already loaded). For the commonly-used add-on packages dplyr/ggplot2/tidyr, installs their headline exported functions into ctx.current_environment.functions via create_r_function over generic any-typed signatures. For any other name, appends an informational warning that the package is not modelled and its exports will resolve to any.
@End Implementation

Process called "load_package_definitions" that takes package_name as String, ctx as RSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Standard packages are already loaded at startup
    Let standard_packages be a list containing "base", "stats", "utils", "graphics", "methods", "grDevices", "datasets"
    For Each std in standard_packages:
        Let is_std be string_values_equal with package_name and std
        If is_std:
            Return
        End If
    End For

    Note: Modelled add-on packages: install their headline exports
    Let is_dplyr be string_values_equal with package_name and "dplyr"
    If is_dplyr:
        Call register_addon_export with "filter" and "dplyr" and ctx
        Call register_addon_export with "select" and "dplyr" and ctx
        Call register_addon_export with "mutate" and "dplyr" and ctx
        Call register_addon_export with "arrange" and "dplyr" and ctx
        Call register_addon_export with "summarise" and "dplyr" and ctx
        Call register_addon_export with "group_by" and "dplyr" and ctx
        Return
    End If

    Let is_tidyr be string_values_equal with package_name and "tidyr"
    If is_tidyr:
        Call register_addon_export with "pivot_longer" and "tidyr" and ctx
        Call register_addon_export with "pivot_wider" and "tidyr" and ctx
        Call register_addon_export with "separate" and "tidyr" and ctx
        Call register_addon_export with "unite" and "tidyr" and ctx
        Return
    End If

    Let is_ggplot be string_values_equal with package_name and "ggplot2"
    If is_ggplot:
        Call register_addon_export with "ggplot" and "ggplot2" and ctx
        Call register_addon_export with "aes" and "ggplot2" and ctx
        Call register_addon_export with "geom_point" and "ggplot2" and ctx
        Call register_addon_export with "geom_line" and "ggplot2" and ctx
        Call register_addon_export with "geom_bar" and "ggplot2" and ctx
        Return
    End If

    Note: Unknown package - exports will resolve to any
    Let warn be string_concat with "Package not modelled, its exports will resolve to any type: " and package_name
    Add warn to end of ctx.warning_list
End Process

@Reasoning:
Installs a single add-on package export into the current environment as a variadic any-returning function. Add-on exports (dplyr verbs, ggplot layers) are highly polymorphic data-pipeline operations, so a variadic any-typed signature is the faithful conservative model that lets call-site analysis proceed without false arity errors.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Builds an RFunction with a single variadic "..." any-typed parameter, return_type=any, the supplied package tag, and the export name, then installs it into ctx.current_environment.functions keyed by that name.
@End Implementation

Process called "register_addon_export" that takes name as String, package as String, ctx as RSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Let dots_param be a value of type RParameter with
        name as "...",
        type as create_any_type,
        has_default as false,
        default_value as 0,
        is_variadic as true
    Let func be a value of type RFunction with
        name as name,
        parameters as a list containing dots_param,
        return_type as create_any_type,
        is_generic as false,
        is_s3_method as false,
        is_s4_method as false,
        package as package
    Set ctx.current_environment.functions at key name to func
End Process